WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:16.299
Okay, let's get started with this model monitoring example.

00:00:16.299 --> 00:00:21.400
So I'm going to open up a new rmarkdown file from a template.

00:00:21.400 --> 00:00:25.879
So I've got all these different templates from, you know, the packages I have installed

00:00:25.879 --> 00:00:29.680
here, and I am going to use a flexdashboard.

00:00:29.680 --> 00:00:35.279
I really like the flexdashboard package for a lot of different situations, like, you know,

00:00:35.279 --> 00:00:42.720
making really pretty shiny apps without much effort, um, to, you know, dashboards that

00:00:42.720 --> 00:00:47.799
I don't want to use shiny with, but I want like a dashboard kind of situation.

00:00:47.799 --> 00:00:49.400
So that's what we're going to use here.

00:00:49.400 --> 00:00:55.680
So I am going to, um, let me save it.

00:00:55.680 --> 00:01:02.560
I'm going to call it this monitor.rmd here, and then the title, so I'm going to, this

00:01:02.560 --> 00:01:09.639
is going to be a dashboard for monitoring a model for traffic crashes.

00:01:09.639 --> 00:01:17.199
So the data here, the data in the model predict the probability that a crash involves an injury.

00:01:17.199 --> 00:01:23.400
It's crashes that are in the city of Chicago, and the data comes from the city of Chicago.

00:01:23.400 --> 00:01:27.919
So we have all this information about what the crashes are like, and then we predict

00:01:27.919 --> 00:01:30.559
whether the crash involved an injury.

00:01:30.559 --> 00:01:37.000
So flexdashboard, we have all these different, it is a very flexible tool, um, you know,

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:39.239
you can do columns or rows.

00:01:39.239 --> 00:01:46.720
I am going to actually change this out and make this, um, the storyboard mode here, which

00:01:46.720 --> 00:01:48.720
is pretty nice.

00:01:48.720 --> 00:01:52.839
And then it turns out that almost all of the logic for the model monitoring is going to

00:01:52.839 --> 00:01:54.639
go here in the setup chunk.

00:01:54.639 --> 00:01:58.279
So we're going to have a really big setup chunk with lots of code, and then actually

00:01:58.279 --> 00:02:01.919
less code down to create the dashboard itself.

00:02:01.919 --> 00:02:06.800
And when it's time to monitor something, I think it's nice to kind of make clear in your

00:02:06.800 --> 00:02:09.399
head what are the pieces that you need.

00:02:09.399 --> 00:02:12.539
And so one piece that you need is your model.

00:02:12.539 --> 00:02:15.839
So your model is deployed somewhere.

00:02:15.839 --> 00:02:21.160
In this case, it's a model that I already trained, I have another video that shows how

00:02:21.160 --> 00:02:22.160
I trained it.

00:02:22.479 --> 00:02:29.240
So it's deployed using a Plumber API on RStudio Connect, but really that model could be anywhere.

00:02:29.240 --> 00:02:33.279
You just need to be able to get to it from R, which of course we have tons of options

00:02:33.279 --> 00:02:35.160
for being able to do that.

00:02:35.160 --> 00:02:40.399
And then you need to get your new data, so the new data that's coming in that you want

00:02:40.399 --> 00:02:45.240
to be able to see how is my model doing with this new data.

00:02:45.240 --> 00:02:50.639
And then your metrics, you know, the metrics that you had back at the testing time and

00:02:50.639 --> 00:02:58.440
then your, you know, the metrics that we would measure over time as we continued to

00:02:58.440 --> 00:02:59.440
move forward.

00:02:59.440 --> 00:03:03.919
So these are kind of the pieces that we need to get going.

00:03:03.919 --> 00:03:06.279
Let us talk about how to get these things.

00:03:06.279 --> 00:03:11.960
So to get the data, often the easiest thing is just to go back to when you trained the

00:03:11.960 --> 00:03:16.520
model.

00:03:16.520 --> 00:03:22.839
This is the GitHub repo where I have all the code I used to train the model originally.

00:03:22.839 --> 00:03:29.119
And so let's just go to the beginning of that whole script and get the code that I used

00:03:29.119 --> 00:03:30.440
to train the model.

00:03:30.440 --> 00:03:36.119
But instead of getting two years of data, let's just get two weeks of data.

00:03:36.119 --> 00:03:42.800
What will happen is as I run this dashboard week after week after week, it will get newer

00:03:42.800 --> 00:03:46.000
and newer crashes as time passes.

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:47.479
So let's run this and make sure it works.

00:03:47.479 --> 00:03:54.320
So what this is doing is it's going to the city of Chicago, getting the new crash data,

00:03:54.320 --> 00:03:59.039
and we have, you know, the information about the weather condition, the traffic way type

00:03:59.039 --> 00:04:03.360
and whatnot, and then whether there was an injury or not.

00:04:03.360 --> 00:04:04.360
So that's one piece.

00:04:04.360 --> 00:04:06.080
We need the new data.

00:04:06.080 --> 00:04:08.580
The next piece we need is we need the model.

00:04:08.580 --> 00:04:13.360
So to handle the model, we're going to use the HTTR package.

00:04:13.360 --> 00:04:17.519
We're going to use JSON Lite.

00:04:17.519 --> 00:04:25.399
The model, in this case, is deployed as a Plumber API on RStudio Connect.

00:04:25.399 --> 00:04:26.799
It doesn't have to be this way, right?

00:04:26.799 --> 00:04:31.279
Like wherever your model is published, you can go and get it from there.

00:04:31.279 --> 00:04:35.559
But this is how I'm going to do it here to demonstrate.

00:04:35.559 --> 00:04:39.640
So this model has a predict endpoint.

00:04:39.640 --> 00:04:45.600
It's got a metrics endpoint that are the testing metrics that we expect to see.

00:04:45.600 --> 00:04:48.320
So I'm going to copy this URL here.

00:04:48.320 --> 00:04:56.640
And then what I'm going to do is I'm going to set up a POST call, and I am going to send

00:04:56.640 --> 00:04:59.880
as the body, I'm going to, it's this crash.

00:04:59.880 --> 00:05:04.679
This crash data is what I'm going to send, but I need to make it to JSON.

00:05:04.679 --> 00:05:07.000
Oh, you know what?

00:05:07.040 --> 00:05:10.839
I don't think I've loaded these yet.

00:05:10.839 --> 00:05:11.320
There we go.

00:05:11.320 --> 00:05:16.040
Okay, so to JSON, and I'm going to do, I'm going to send it crash.

00:05:16.040 --> 00:05:19.119
I'm not going to send the injuries though.

00:05:19.119 --> 00:05:22.119
And then, so that would give me the result.

00:05:22.119 --> 00:05:34.640
And then I want the text as UTF-8, and that will be JSON at that point.

00:05:34.640 --> 00:05:37.440
So I'm going to do from JSON.

00:05:37.440 --> 00:05:45.839
So these are predictions like so, like that.

00:05:45.839 --> 00:05:47.399
So let's run this.

00:05:47.399 --> 00:05:49.760
So these now are predictions.

00:05:49.760 --> 00:05:55.799
So it's sending for all of those new crashes that I have that I want to use for monitoring.

00:05:55.799 --> 00:06:01.519
It's sending them to the model, getting predictions for them, and then handling,

00:06:01.519 --> 00:06:04.839
you know, all of the output here and getting back.

00:06:04.839 --> 00:06:12.760
So what we have at the end there, let me do it like this, is a vector like this.

00:06:12.760 --> 00:06:17.920
So it's a vector, and these are probabilities of having injuries.

00:06:17.920 --> 00:06:23.279
We have our new crash data, we have our model, and then let's put it together

00:06:23.279 --> 00:06:25.600
and find our metrics.

00:06:25.600 --> 00:06:36.600
So we take that crash data and let's bind on, let's call it predict underscore pred injuries.

00:06:36.600 --> 00:06:38.880
So we just bind that on together.

00:06:38.880 --> 00:06:42.839
So now we have a column of predicted probabilities.

00:06:42.839 --> 00:06:56.600
Let's make a column of hard class predictions.

00:06:56.600 --> 00:07:08.839
So if this thing that I just made is greater than 0.5, let's call it injuries,

00:07:08.839 --> 00:07:11.239
and if it's not, let's call it none.

00:07:11.239 --> 00:07:13.720
So this now matches these.

00:07:13.720 --> 00:07:17.200
So I'm making a hard class prediction.

00:07:17.200 --> 00:07:24.440
I think I need to say if anything is a character, I need to change it to a factor.

00:07:24.440 --> 00:07:25.600
Right, there we go.

00:07:25.600 --> 00:07:32.920
Okay, so because the function that I'm about to use needs factors, and those functions are

00:07:32.920 --> 00:07:35.640
from the yardstick package.

00:07:35.640 --> 00:07:44.720
So the yardstick package is from tidymodels, and you can use it with models that have been

00:07:44.720 --> 00:07:49.000
trained with tidymodels, or you can use it with, you know, any other kinds of models

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:50.920
and get out these nice results.

00:07:50.920 --> 00:07:56.160
Actually, before I started working for RStudio or using tidymodels at all,

00:07:56.160 --> 00:07:57.000
I used yardstick.

00:07:57.000 --> 00:08:01.200
Yardstick was actually the first part of this whole ecosystem that I used at all

00:08:01.200 --> 00:08:02.959
because it is so nice.

00:08:02.959 --> 00:08:11.920
And so we can do metrics, and the way we do it is we say the true value is in injuries,

00:08:11.920 --> 00:08:18.519
and then we can say predicted and pred injuries, so it's the hard class and then the class

00:08:18.519 --> 00:08:24.760
probabilities like this, and it gives us accuracy, ROC, and you look at this,

00:08:24.760 --> 00:08:26.000
you're like, is this bad?

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:31.359
Is this worse than what we expect based on how the things did at testing?

00:08:31.359 --> 00:08:32.640
This is what we want to know.

00:08:32.640 --> 00:08:38.039
We probably want to do a little bit more because this is for that whole two weeks,

00:08:38.039 --> 00:08:45.239
and we probably want to add a little bit more in here and say mutate, so we've got a...

00:08:45.239 --> 00:08:46.919
What's it called?

00:08:46.919 --> 00:08:48.640
Crash date.

00:08:48.640 --> 00:08:49.679
Crash date.

00:08:49.679 --> 00:08:52.479
So we're going to do a little bit of some rounding here.

00:08:52.479 --> 00:08:54.799
Actually, let's do floor date.

00:08:54.799 --> 00:09:01.760
Say as date, crash date, and then we're going to say unit equals week.

00:09:01.760 --> 00:09:06.760
So now we're rounding by the week that we have, and then we're just going to group

00:09:06.760 --> 00:09:10.359
by that crash date like this.

00:09:10.359 --> 00:09:12.000
So now we have it for these...

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:18.479
We've got three beginnings of weeks in this data set, so we have these different values here.

00:09:18.479 --> 00:09:26.919
So these are the metrics by week like this that we have.

00:09:26.919 --> 00:09:33.440
And if we are starting out our model metrics, let's say we just trained our model,

00:09:33.440 --> 00:09:37.359
and we are starting out, we would probably take this.

00:09:37.359 --> 00:09:42.039
Let's say we trained our model on, you know, March 20th.

00:09:42.039 --> 00:09:46.280
We would start this, and it would be time for us to start keeping track of this.

00:09:46.280 --> 00:09:53.559
And I think a great way to do this is the pins package.

00:09:53.559 --> 00:09:57.719
I'm using the development version of pins as of, you know, this recording.

00:09:57.719 --> 00:09:59.440
It will go to CRAN soon.

00:09:59.440 --> 00:10:05.479
But if you see me use, you know, some of the functions and things, they might look a little

00:10:05.479 --> 00:10:10.039
different than what's on CRAN right now, but those functions will go there soon.

00:10:10.039 --> 00:10:18.599
And so what we want to do is I actually have some stored metrics in a pin right now.

